And out of nowhere I decided to participate in a race which is in particular a full circle around the mountain near Sofia - Vitosha mountain. The race is completely offroad in the mountain and with mountain bikes - a very tough race for a complete newbie like me. And the distance is 100km. So, I managed to finish and I was so happy! Since then, I have been riding mountain bike for 5 years already and it has become more than a hobby - maybe a passion.
So, never say you won't ride bicycle again, you don't know what you are missing. :) I hope you are well now and do what you love. Cheers!

On my first classic style multi day cycle tour, I burned (totally over worked) my legs on my first day pushing 132km into the mountains. That was in 1987 I was 39.  I was in agony for five days. Today I cannot think of travelling without my trike. I have made a lot of mistakes but I have never let them stop me and I have learned from them. Travelling/touring by bike will bring you in touch with so many people and the experiences will change you. So tell your stories and listen to the stories of others. When bad things happen, start looking for the good things as they are always there. If two bad thing happen I tend to get really excited. Everything always works out. A friend and cycle tourer, who is heading on the downhill to 90, said to me once and I translated into Latin "Satis est tempus instituendi dum in itinere." or "There is time enough to train on tour.". I prefer maps as it lends a different perspective to the journey, though I always carry a smart phone (no data plan) and a GPS with OSM.  And don't over plan, though it is always good to have an idea where the choke points might be.

Thanks for the video, it was very interesting :) Your grandfather must've been a very fascinating person and it would be cool to read those journals in english. Also this video is very informative and I've learned pretty much the same things when I was riding around Lithuania last year:
1. Don't push yourself into deadlines.
2. Kilometers don't matter.
3. Be here and now. Just enjoy the moment.
4. Stay positive. Find ways how to keep positive attitude.
There are many ways to ruin a journey and to make it unbearable. But people who do it more often, know how to create a great experience.

This reminded me of my first long distance tour I made as a 22 yo lad. I had been a regular bike commuter before, but that commute was 5..7 km one trip.
Next thing I knew I cycled across France in 5 days to arrive at the sea as quickly as possible. Longest day trip 225 km, not something I would recommend (nor something I could do anymore; bones to creaky...) good thing about this: the following three weeks around Brittany at 50..100 km a day were a breeze...
I recently revived this tour, but just the Brittany part. Still fun to be in the saddle and experience the countryside.

I quickly went back to paper maps on my last tour (Brittany, France) Keeping a smartphone powered on a trip where you often camp in the rough is just too much of a  hassle (even if I have a good charger driven by the hub dynamo.)

Eva,
Wanted to share with you.
80 years ago on June 1941 my mother escaped with her family their little town in Artsiz, Bessarabia because of the German invasion and ended up in Cheptura, Tajikistan where they stayed till the war was over.
My father escaped his home in Lodz, Polland after the Germans invaded it, escaped to the USSR, was arrested in Grodno as a Polish soldjer and sent to Siberia were he stayed till the German's invaded the USSR, and went to Tajikistan.
So, they both went to Tajikistan - my Father from Arkhangelsk in Siberia and my mother from Artsiz in Bessarabia beginning July 1941.
They met and married there and after the war returned. Their families murdered their property robbed - there was no room for then in Europe anymore and founf refuge in DC Camps.
I was born in a DC Camp in Germany near Berchtersgarten - in a big mansion that was in a German military airport where Hitler used to stay when he flew there on his way to Berchtersgarten, and turned by the American army a hospital for DC's after the war.
Hilter started the war with Poland and invaded the USSR, making my parents flee to Tajikistan and meet there. Methink some justice was done to be born in his mansion...
I'm 74 now, live in Israel where my parents came to in 1948, and when the skies open after the Corona, intend to follow my parent's voyage during and right after the war.
Start in this little town in Bessarabia (now Ukraine), follow my mother's jurney: through Ukraine, Russia, Azerbaijan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan.
Then back to Russia where I intend to find the graves of My Mother's father (which I'm named after him) who is burried in Novosibirsk near his son that was a soldier in the Red Army, got sick and died one day after his father came from Tajikistan to see his health, went sick too on the way, and the two are burried together.
Visit my Father's home in Lodz and his father's grave there, and a place in Germany where my father was kept as a Polish pow and escaped from there making his way by foot at nights all the way to Lodz.
Visit the museum in a Lodz train station from where my Father's two sisters were sent to be suffocated in chelmno, and visit where their bones laid bare till few years ago together with some 250,000 Jews murdered near the small Polish village there.
My father escaped his home right after they were shipped to the Lodz Getto, but only one of his three sisters was willing to go along with him.
Follow my parents' way through Russia, Ukraine, Poland, Czech Republic, Austria, Germany - where I was born in Ainring, the southest town in Germany.
There I'll end my tour (My parents and me came to Israel with a ship from Marseille).
It's all together about 15,000 km (excludindg the flights from and back Israel).
What do you say/advice, if at all, as a traveller, to me? Thanks in any case :-)

Thanks for the likes to whomever gave them :-)

Waiting for the skies to open so I can go to Artsiz and begin my trip.

Had today an encounter that might be a good omen. Went to the market in Haifa to by carps for my wife to prepare gefilte fish for the Seder night. Waiting for the seller to cut and prepare them - a lady waiting there too tells me someting in Russian.

"Sory, I don't speak Russian". "My mother does, she is from Bessarbia". The lady smiles a big one: "I'm from Kishinev !" (Kishinev - Chișinău in Romanian - is the Capital city of today's Moldova, in the past in Bessarabia).

I tell her that my mother is from Artsiz (a vlitle town in Bessrabia, today part of Ukraine). The lady's smile turns wider. "My mother is from Artsiz!!" Turns out the lady lives in Kisinev and came to Isreal to visit her mother that lives here now.

Took her phone number to give my mother, that is now 96, thanks God, healthy, bright and intelligent as ever. Almost all her friends and family from youth are already in a better world and she was very hapy for the oportunity to speak with someone from Bessarbia.

To meet at random in a market in Haifa, Israel someone born in the small town of Artsiz in former Besarabia - is, I gather, a good omen for me to indeed make that journey :-)

Wow! Your bike trip here was something that was similar to my own solo 14-day "Tour de Malaysia" in 2001. At that time there was no real smartphone & all I used to navigate was my Lonely Planet: Malaysia travel book. Like you, I hardly trained & I was so spartan for my trip - just 2 sets of quick-dry clothes (one to wear & wash to dry overnight, the other to wear for the day). I had no laptop, iPad & definitely no drone during those days... My total little backpack was 5kg & ironically, after the first day, I threw away my brand new sleeping bag (took off a whole load of weight off my back). :P

Watching your video here totally brought back a lot of old memories almost 2 decades ago. Loved your grandpa's quotes & even though you broke down on the day you had to ride your bike on your flip-flops. That was both a moment of Strength (as you fight with the internal struggles within your mind) & also, even comical when you were complaining about the hassle of needing to pee. :D

I also remembered all the interesting people whom I had met along the journey & similarly, had commented how "brave" I was to do this trip all by myself. Dziękuję again... for showing a rare part of Polska that is off the beaten track. :)

I did my first solo from Boston to Key West at age 58...the most terrifying thing was the morning I left. So many reasons not to go but there wasn’t one day I regretted going. 41 days, 2200 miles, stealth Ed camped every night in the woods! After I got there I swore never again! Mentally and physically brutal! Last September I must have forgotten how difficult it was because I went on another solo trip from Boston attempting to reach San Diego,CA. Once upon a time I did a 500 mile bicycle trek across eastern Oklahoma.  It was done every year and we started with 1500 people.  Middle of the first day we were struck with multiple tornadoes, all around us.  Torrential rains, unbelievable winds, all you could do was hunker down under a bush or something and hang on for dear life.  They eventually passed and the second day only 500 continued on.  But the people who stayed we fantastic and I look back on that week as the best vacation I ever took.

I am a cyclist who travels in Europe. I followed and met so many lonely people or couples on simple bicycles even on a trottinette kickboard (without assistance) crossing the world, particularly hostile environment, deserts ... So to see a strong and young woman, who feels like she has made a feat by traveling 9 days with certainly difficult times but in nature, without excessive heat or cold, without pollution, without rationing or particular danger. And to conclude that she will never ride a bicycle again, I find that negative and very imature! You reminded me of those American women who live in front of screens and whose only exploits are shopping. I hope you grow mentally and go on real expeditions where you have to draw your strength to survive or at least achieve a real challenge. On the other hand, well done for the variety of shots with the addition of a drone, it was well done. Also, you could have taken the time to explore the cultural, historical side. Sometimes, it brings a human touch to take an interest in local people, especially the elderly, through interviews.

Cycle touring is great fun really...if you don't obsess about a destination.   How?    Don't have a destination.   Just start cycling in the morning and stop when feel tired.   Being able to go wild camping helps.   Wild camping is more fun than official campsites too.  Using your phone and apps can help you find a place sleep that's really close by.    Also too cycle really slowly so that at no point is it strenuous.    Get special low gearing for the bike to help with hills.   Also too don't "break" the chain and keep it on those wheelie things...;-)  lol.

Bike touring does not require massive touring experence, but planning is a great help. I have bicycled around Atlantic Canada, Quebec, Maine, and Vermont.

A good bike with a large range gearing, lights, racks etc is better. Print maps are fine. Wet shoes can be warn with shoping bags over the socks. Although I'd have checked to see if the campground had laundry facilities (washer/dryer) to dry your shoes and maybe your tent. You were very brave to bike using flipflops.

If you are looking for an extreme cycling adventure consider crossing Canada West to East.

My thoughts for anyone thinking of cycle touring or bikepacking look for packing checklists they may make your adventure more fun and satisifying!

Just think just 25 years ago I cycled across the USA "with only paper maps to guide me."  When I was done with a state map I sent it home in the mail with notes on it. I had drawn a line from Gainesville Florida to Seattle, wa and then best fit the entirety and exit points for that line. We rode 3200 miles in 43 days. Only one day off in Lawrence Kansas.  Longest dat 117 miles marion arkansas to searcy arkansas with tail wind.  Shortest day was 35 miles toward helena montana with head wind. Crossed the continental divide at lolo pass and went downhill across the whole state of idaho on hwy 12. Literally, downhill the whole way. Exactly like I predicted as the road ran next to the river flowing west.

People (including me ;-) ) have been traveling with paper maps only for centuries - you probably just too young to remember those times, haha...! But I admit: I love GPS technology and the internet makes things so much easier. With paper maps you either get large area coverage (if you need to safe weight and cary only a few maps) but sacrifice details. Or you take the detailed maps and carry a kilogram of paper. So yes, I admit, modern technology has made things much easier. For trip planning at home I still prefer a combination of paper and GPS, because on the screen you always loose the details when you need large area coverage. Not so on paper maps. In any case: looks like you had a great and challenging trip! Poland? I have never been there! But maybe next hear, if Covid-19 permits! Greetings from Sweden - Kai-Uwe / www.nordicbiker.se

I think that by tackling too many miles, you ruined cycling for yourself.  Get back on the bike.  You'll be glad you did.  And while you're at it, raise your seat.  The muscles that do the most work when you cycle are strongest when they are at their extension.  With your seat too low, you're not getting the most out of your legs.  It's too tiring.  And it'll take a toll on your lower back as well.  But bicycling is the best way to travel.  It allows for better interaction with the locals.  The colors are brighter and the smells are more potent.  And the food tastes better.  Especially when you feel you've "earned it."

When seeing you becoming frustrated on your journey. Something that I use, especially as a cognitive neuroscientist, is to redirect your brain. When you feel too frustrated and down, try not to focus on your destination, but rather take a moment to look where you are. Question what makes this location, region, different or special. Sometimes write these down in your notes. Take deep breaths and enjoy that moment. Also think of what you have done and keep yourself grounded in the moment by looking at things to keep positive, such as scenery, natural beauty, etc. Essentially whatever works. ** Chronicles of adventure: **
I have lost all my rush,
Kilometers no longer impress me
Whether there’s 100, 200, or 600 of them,
I’m indifferent to that because I have to cross that distance anyway.
So I’m not scared of distances anymore.
And the same applies to time,
Whether I meant to be on the road for 3 hours or 17,
What’s the difference?
Either way, I have to reach my destination.

I don’t get stressed out by the slow,
Sometimes tortoise-like speeds.
I simply get into my vehicle,
And I ride as far and for as long in absolute peace
Until I reach the destination that I set for myself.

I also don’t let the discomforts bother me,
Such as tough seat, the heat, the dust, or the lack of water,
All of this in its own way is beautiful and wonderful.

Whoever cannot adapt to this kind of life,
Or in fact, whoever cannot come to love this kind of life,
Cannot be a true traveler.

** To be a true traveler requires character. **

The quote-

I've noticed one thing changed in me, I've lost all my rushes. Kilometres no longer impress me, whether they are 200, 400 or 600. I am indifferent to that, because I have to cross that distance anyway. So I'm not scared of distances any more.

And the same applies to time. Whether I'm in the road for three hours or seventeen, what's the difference? Either way, I have to reach my destination. I don't get stressed out by the slow, sometimes tortoise-like speeds.

I simply get into my vehicle and I ride as far and for as long in absolute peace until I reach the destination that I've set for myself. I also don't let the discomforts such as tough sit, the hit, the dust or the lack of water bother me.

All of this in its own way is beautiful and wonderful. Whoever cannot adapt to this kind of life or in fact, whoever cannot come to love this kind of life, cannot be a true traveller. To be a true traveller requires character.

I always seem to been with Polish people, I grew up in a city in the Midlands which has had a large Polish population for generations and now there are at least a million Polish people in the UK. Yet I have never known a Polish person very well and know very little about the country. Your vlog shows what a beautiful and still largely rural country it is, ideal for cyclists.
At the low point of your trip you tried to cycle in flip flops because you had left your trainers outside all night and they were soaked. I would honestly not have done that because flip flops are just ... floppy ... and waste your energy flopping about when you want a good connection with the pedals on your bike. I would have worn the trainers and put dry socks on. Wash the wet socks and hang them on the back of your bike to dry in the breeze. By lunchtime your trainers would have dried out with your body heat and if it is a nice day the socks you washed would have dried out also.
Have you read a book by Tim Moore called French Revolutions? It is about someone without a great deal of cycling experience who decided to cycle an entire course of the Tour.
Despite what you said at the end of your vlog I am convinced you will cycle again, but on a better bike. In car terms £200 in the UK gets you a Dacia, £600 a Ford or a Skoda and £1000 a BMW. All very affordable for most people in work.

You're probably young enough to be my granddaughter, but I watched this because you did it without Google Maps. (And also because I want to do some touring in Poland, though would stay further north than you did.) Twenty-five years ago I used to talk to a lot more people along the way to ask about roads, local history, etc. Now I don't talk to people so much, because I have Google Maps, a route programmed into my bicycle computer, and do a lot of history research ahead of time. So I have fewer questions to ask. I miss those older ways and think it's great that you did it the way you did. You may inspire me to try something like that again. I'd have trouble doing it in Poland, though. I recognized a few words from your conversations, but wouldn't be able to follow difficult directions.

As for your wet shoes, those can be a real problem as wet socks can chafe your feet, and then you'll really have problems. One technique I and others have used is to put on dry socks, then plastic bread bags over the socks, and then the shoes. It still is troublesome because your feet will sweat inside the bread bags if you do it for a long period, but it can help if you don't push too hard.

That is quite an accomplishment to ride 60 miles a day in hilly country, without training, with a camping rig a bit heavier than mine, and regular street shoes without clips. Your grandfather definitely would have reason to be proud of you. I hope it isn't the end of your bicycle touring, no matter what you said at the end of your ride.

Wonderful video Eva. Takes me back to 1981- I was 17 - my first overseas adventure. Train from Penzance, cycle across London, train and ferry to Esbjerg, then cycle to Flensburg (to see a girl - of course). And back. GPS was 12 years in the future - but I used hostels not a tent, so less kit. Planning on paper maps and route cards...

As was said - you are a brave and strong young woman - and I completely understand how much easier travelling alone is, and why you'd want to do it. Somehow I lost the wanderlust - never cycle toured again - settled down and stopped travelling. Don't think you ever will - and if travel makes you happy, then we're all delighted to watch the results

Your grandfather would be proud of you (and how you share your journeys in the modern world). You have the qualities he required - you are a true traveller.

I was struck by Eva's Grandpa's words so I wrote them out. I hope you enjoy them as much as I did.
If she would tell me his name, I would love to quote him and attribute the words to him by name.

“I’ve noticed one thing changing in me. I’ve lost all my rush.

Kilometers no longer impress me.
Whether there is 100, 200, or 600 of them, I’m indifferent because I have to cross that distance anyway, So I’m not scared of distances anymore.
And the same applies to time.
Whether I’m meant to be on the road 3 hours or 17, What’s the difference? Either way I have to reach my destination.

I don’t get stressed out by the slow, sometimes tortoise like speeds. I simply get into my vehicle and I ride as far and as long, in absolute peace until I’ve reached the destination that I have set for myself.

I also don’t let the discomforts bother me, such as a tough seat, the heat, the dust, or the lack of water.

All of this in its own way is beautiful and wonderful.
Whoever cannot adapt to this kind of life, or in fact, whoever cannot come to LOVE this kind of life, cannot be a true traveler.

To be a true traveler requires character.”

~Eva's Grandpa.

100 km might be reasonable in Poland.
But Norway, Switzerland, Iceland, that kind of places have rough terrain, so if you ever decide to go to those places do yourself a favor and give yourself a little more leeway in terms of time, both so you don't have to push yourself so hard, but also so you get more time to just experience the view and possibly even take a detour to see things if you get some spare time. =)

Oh, Oh. One of the drone views of you cycling: RED FLAG. Respect for the 90..110km per day, by the way. 8:02 It's the SADDLE height that is TOO LOW. The best height is where you pedal with your toes, stretch your leg completely and need to stretch your foot a bit at the deepest point. The moment you need to wiggle your hips to maintain contact with the pedals, you are too high. It's simple mechanics (that physics thing) where forces at the wrong angle can be decomposed in two perpendicular angle parts. When you sit too low, you loose a lot of force in the angles in your joints. And you stress the connecting tissue around the joints more, as well as the tendons between muscles and bones. A way to measure saddle height is inside leg and add 10% for shoe and toe stretching - as a start: back against a wall for support, feet flat on the ground, not too far apart, clamp book with the back of the cover between your legs with the back of the book horizontal. Measure from floor to back of book and add 10%. Transfer that to saddle at deepest point to top of saddle.

A trooper for effort and persistence!

Next time planning these trips, I suggest to analyze "height meters", not just distance. That height information is missing in most "old fashioned maps" except when you go back to the 1:20,000 or so that every country had - you would need a lot of maps if you wanted to bring them with you, though. Those maps have "height" lines and how close they are indicate the steepness. Really, as a cyclist you need to take the trouble to do that climb-descend analysis in planning. For this kind of trip, in say 1975, I would have tried to get hold of the 1:20,000 maps and they would have shown the streets in the villages and towns too.

Przykre jest to że Polka z takimi zasiegami na yt wysyła taki obraz Polski w świat. Polski zacofanej i biednej. Boli tym bardziej, że Polska naprawdę tak nie wygląda a żeby znaleźć takie rozpadające się budynki na polskiej zamieszkanej wsi trzeba bardzo się natrudzic. In 2017, (it was an ambition I had after a serious event in my life) I travelled by train from London to Brussels onto Cologne, up to Oldenburg, then through to Hanover, Berlin, into Poland (Poznan), Wroclaw, Rzeszow (150Km) from Ukrainian border, and back to Krakow, Katowice and finally a flight back to UK. Like you, I remember lots and lots of forests. It was an amazing journey and experience. The old town of Rzeszow was something I will always especially remember. I'd like to return and go to Halicz and Bolszowce in the Ukraine to see where my family came from.
Am looking forward to viewing your other video diaries.

I had the weirdest thing happened to me in Bergen after a long bikepacking weekend in August. I met a veteran while I was sitting on a park bench. After talking for a couple of hours, he ended up giving me a WW1 medal. When you bike, you meet so many random and memorable people. That's why I love it.

During the summer, I invite people to bike in Norway. The best route in my opinion has to be to take the train from Oslo to Geilo, which is at the top of the central mountain plateau. From here go west, and then it's all down hill via the fjords to Bergen. Mostly downhill, few cars, but moderate fitness is a must when you cross Finse. Every inch of that road is super picturesque.

Temperatures vary between 0 degree C at night, incl. some snow patches, to 25 C. in the low lands. I recommend a 3 season bag and clothes to regulate your temperature. Be creative, like 2 trash bags and some duck tape can turn into an emergency bicy sack to raise your temperature by 5 C degrees.

People say it's expensive here. That's true, IF you stay at hotels. When I was bikepacking, there's the Allemannsretten, which means you can camp anywhere that's 150 m. from houses. It all cost me 10$ for food at the grocery store during those three days. Train ride back to Oslo (incl. bike) cost me 50$ during the night. Sun all the way, no tire punctures and super friendly people all the way. By far my best trip.

Pics: http://imgur.com/gallery/l6pqone

GREAT GREAT FILMMAKING! I had been following the journey on IG and really pleased to see how you stitched the experience all together here. I give you praise first for the inspiration, as it's so important to inspire joy through travel, ESPECIALLY in times when people find it hard to create new experiences or even just live their life at all.

Secondly, I offer you praise for your creative expression and storytelling. From planning, to purpose, the visual storytelling was excellent, with a clear and relatable overlaying narrative. I have seen many other travel documentaries now that were incoherent with lazy gaps in the itinerary or missing narration that leaves you confused (I AM LOOKING AT YOU "PEDAL THE WORLD" by FELIX STARCK, how did Netflix purchase that?!).

What I liked about yours is that I was along on the journey, understood precisely your route, your emotional perseverance, and feelings of accomplishment. It's really impressed and motivated me to keep up the adventures in difficult times. Thank you also for inspiring me to tackle similar adventures here in Ireland and fanning the flames of the wanderlust for fellow travelers. I hope you keep honing this craft and start getting big studio attention, you deserve it for your dedication.... Keep up the great mission.

Any one considering to cross a country by bike there are lessons to be learned:  Have the right gear. Not expensive gear! Just prepare the right gear.   Have a quality bike that works perfectly.  Have repair sets and spare bike tubes and learn how to change them.  Have a good saddle.  Did I mention a GOOD saddle?  Have your bike set up for your body measurements. It is so much more easy to bike when you are riding a good set up bike!  Use navigation tools! How romantic Eva's motivation might be .. your experience will be much better if you know you go the right way.  Do SOME exercise.. try out your bike so you can still adapt your set up before sailing off.  Wear bike pants and not a suit to facilitate peeing experience ;-)  And last and not least: Go to the Netherlands (beginners experience) or Belgium (Next level). The Netherlands has absolutely a fantastic biking infrastructure and beautiful landscapes and villages.  Not too much elevation in general but if you like a bit of climbing ... I can recommend some pretty challenging areas in the middle of nature.  If you go to Belgium: Infrastructure not always as perfect as in The Netherlands and more challenging elevations but no mountains :-) But still a marvelous country to cross and have an excellent adventure. Both countries have a touristic bike routes network clearly marked by numbers so it is very easy to navigate and be guided to the best paths (separated from car- and truck traffic!!! ) and sights all over both countries!

I've noticed one thing changing in me.
I've lost all my rush.
Kilometers is no longer impress me.
Whether there's 100,200 or 600 of them, I'm indifferent to that, because I have to cross that distance anyway.
So I'm not scared of distances anymore.
And the same applies to time, whether I'm meant to be on the road three hours or 17.
What's the difference.
Either way, I have to reach my destination.
I don't get stressed out by the slow, sometimes tortoise-speeds.
I simply get into my vehicle, and I ride as far and for as long.
in absolute peace, until I reach the destination that I have set for myself.
I also don't let the discomforts bother me, such as the tough seat, the heat, the dust, or the lack of water.
All of this, in its own way, is beautiful and wonderful.
Whoever cannot adapt to this kind of life, or in fact, whoever cannot come to love this kind of life, cannot be a true traveler.
To be a true traveler requires character.

I have noticed one thing change in me
I have lost all rush
Kilometers no longer impress me
Whether there is 100, 200 or 700 of them
I'm different to that
Because i have to cross that distance anyway

And the same applies to time

In absolute peace

Such as tough seat, the heat, the dust or the lack of water

Whoever cannot adapt this kind of life
Or in fact, whoever cannot come to love this kind of life
Cannot be a true traveller
To be a true traveller requires character

EVA: Going across country with paper map.
ME: Still drawing my Travel Plan on a paper.

Paper maps are perfectly good. Just make sure you have detailed ones of the areas you plan to travel through. A little bit of planning before the trip is well worth it. Make a list of all your waypoints set about 20Km apart (for a bike trip) and tick them off as you pass by. You will now how far you went and how far there is still to go. I do this when going for long multi-day hikes in the mountains although my waypoints are 500m apart because many sections are off track and I don't want to get lost. Detailed maps and waypoints! :)
